    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters April 21st with a high-upside lineup, headlined by **Corbin Carroll** (87.14) and **James Wood** (78.42). **Corbin Carroll** is our primary engine today; facing Sean Burke, he benefits from a favorable park factor and a slow pitcher delivery profile that heavily incentivizes his elite stolen base potential. Similarly, **James Wood** is in a prime spot leading off against Reynaldo L\u00f3pez, whose 6.36 xERA presents a massive opportunity for early-inning production. We also see high-floor value from **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Trevor Story** (72.05), both of whom benefit significantly from soft matchups against Randy V\u00e1squez and Luis Gil, respectively, while **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.01) and **Brice Turang** (71.53) round out a strong core of starters who provide reliable, efficient contributions across our 5x5 categories.\n\nThe optimizer faced a difficult choice at the utility slot, ultimately favoring **Josh Naylor** (51.19) over **Alex Freeland** (49.73). While **Alex Freeland** remains a high-potential asset, his marginal projected output against Landen Roupp\u2014coupled with a 35% rain risk\u2014kept him on the bench in favor of **Josh Naylor**. Elsewhere, we are monitoring **Dalton Rushing** (51.38) with caution; while his power-hitting profile is appealing, the 35% rain risk and a difficult draw against Landen Roupp necessitate a watchful eye. Meanwhile, veteran bats like **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Austin Riley**, and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** remain on the bench today, as their respective matchups against elite arms like Connelly Early and Foster Griffin suppress their scoring efficiency below our current thresholds. We will continue to monitor lineups, particularly for **Luis Campusano**, **Dalton Rushing**, and **Kyle Karros**, as these late-order bats are highly sensitive to finalized lineup positions.",
